Public Art Fund Archive

Contents

Series I: City Walls

Scope and Content

This series documents the activities of City Walls Inc. Materials include administrative documents, financial records, plans, drawings, publications and photographs that provide insight into the planning, execution, and dismantling of the City Walls mural projects. The files are arranged chronologically. Series I is broken down into three subseries.

Subseries I.A: Administrative Files, 1967-1978

Extent

1 boxes

Scope and Content

This series includes general correspondence, tax returns, financial records, consulting files, and general publicity efforts during the period from 1968 to 1978. This series also contains some of the background documentation in obtaining wall locations for murals.

Subseries I.B: Artist Files

Scope and Content

Arranged chronologically this series documents individual projects commissioned and produced by City Walls. Materials include contract information, correspondence with artists and contractors, and promotional materials. Project folders also contain sketches, plans, photographs of sites and installations, contact sheets and slides. Significant chronological gaps exist, with documentation missing on artists who participated in the program from 1967 to around 1970.

Series II: Public Arts Council

Scope and Content

Arranged chronologically, this series documents projects that were initiated by the Public Arts Council of the Municipal Arts Society. Significant gaps exist and the materials are not a comprehensive reflection of all projects completed during the time period. The series is divided into six subseries.

Series III: Percent for Art

Scope and Content

Materials in this series document the formation of New York City's Percent for Art program. This includes drafts of legislation, rules and procedures, budget documents, general correspondence with the Department of Cultural Affairs, and research material on nation-wide Percent for Art programs.

The series is divided into four subseries.

Subseries III.A: Lobbying and Legislation

Scope and Content

Arranged chronologically, the folders in this series include information on federal, state, and city legislation, consisting of proposals and drafts of legislation, senate reports, congressional records, and art and architecture hearing documentation. There is also research on out of state legislation and correspondence from out of state representatives. Materials include a list of committee members who helped start the project in New York, budget and contract drafts, correspondence with Doris Freedman, the National Endowment the Arts, the House of Representatives and a White House letter from Richard Nixon.

Subseries III.B: Project Planning, 1983-19941983-1986

Scope and Content

Arranged chronologically, materials in this series documents Percent for Art activity from 1983-1986.This includes general correspondence with the Department of Cultural Affairs, information about the current state of the program, procedures, rules and regulations, and research material on nation-wide Percent for Art programs. Much of the correspondence is between Susan K. Freedman and The Department of Cultural Affairs, including meeting agendas, implementation procedures, and information on the East Harlem Art-park project. The series also includes folders from research the Public Art Fund conducted in 1994, regarding procedures for de-accessioning public artwork.

Series V: Messages to the Public

Scope and Content

This series documents an extensive 10-year series of artist works that were screened on the Spectacolor lightboard in Times Square from 1982 to 1990. The "Messages to the Public" series began with Keith Haring and included Jenny Holzer's first Light-emitting diode project, featured computer-generated messages by over 70 artists.

Subseries V.A: Artist Files

Scope and Content

Arranged alphabetically by each artist's surname, material in this series includes contract information, correspondence with the artist, proposals, promotional material, and photographs. Some folders also contain original sketches and prototypes designed by each artist.

In certain cases, Spectacolor Inc, exercised editorial control and did not run projects by all artists, including the work of Judith Barry and Nancy Spero. In most cases, folders pertaining to these projects have been labeled "unrealized."

Subseries V.B: Administrative Files, 1982-1992

Scope and Content

This series includes correspondence with and documentation of Spectacolor Inc., the activities of the selection panel, financial and budgeting information, and general publicity material. This series also includes some of the background documentation on the compilation videotapes that the Public Art Fund made of various animations from Messages To The Public.

Subseries VI.B: In the Public Realm

Scope and Content

Arranged chronologically, this series documents Public Art Fund's In The Public Realm program, initiated by director Tom Eccles in 1995 to support public art projects by New York-based emerging artists. Materials include documentation of realized projects, as well as proposals from In the Public Realm finalists.

Subseries VI.C: MetroTech Center

Scope and Content

Arranged chronologically, this series documents projects that were realized at MetroTech Center in Brooklyn, New York. Public Art Fund began organizing new exhibitions at MetroTech Center in 1993 through a partnership with MetroTech Commons Associates and MetroTech companies. These group exhibitions include work by multiple artists at the site. Materials include administrative information pertaining to each exhibition, as well as folders on each individual artist participating the project.

Subseries VI.G: Doris Freedman Award, 1988

Extent

The Doris c. Freedman Award was established in 1982 by Executive Order of Mayor Edward I. Koch. "This Award shall be presented annually to an individual or organization selected by the Mayor in recognition of a contribution to the people of the City of New York that greatly enriches the public environment." Award for outstanding efforts to enrich public places in the city with works of art... The award is a tribute to the city's first Cultural Affairs Director, Doris C. Freedman. The award is presented annually on April 25th to commemorate Mrs. Freedman's birthday.

Scope and Content

This series includes information on recipients of The Doris C. Freedman Award, which was established in 1982 in honor of Public Art Fund Founder Doris Freedman. The award recognizes an individual or organization for a contribution to the people of the City of New York that greatly enriches the public environment. This series includes significant gaps, with no documentation included between 1995 and 2007.

Series VIII: Susan Freedman Papers

Scope and Content

This series contains material collected by Susan Freedman from 1981-1996. Daughter of Doris Freedman, Susan Freedman has served as the President of the Public Art Fund since 1986. The organization of this series reflects the original order of the papers.

Series IX: Photographic Material

Scope and Content

The photographs in this series do not include photos from all Public Art Fund projects. The bulk of the project photographs are found within each project folder in series I, II, III, and V.

Subseries IX.A: City Walls Slides, 1967-1977

Scope and Content

This series includes slides and negatives from multiple artist projects commissioned by City Walls. The images document the installation and inception of each project.

Series X: Video

Scope and Content

This series contains all video recordings from the Public Art Fund Archive. Items are arranged chronologically by date of creation, and then alphabetically by title. Material includes video documentation of artist projects, recorded news broadcasts, and interviews with artists. This series includes videotaped footage of "Messages to the Public", shot at Times Square over a ten-year period. Descriptions are derived from the original cassette or container annotations and include title, date, the original format of video, and the total running time (TRT).

Series XII: Audio

Scope and Content

This series contains audio recordings from the Public Art Fund Archive. The audio consists of recordings of lectures, panel discussions, interviews, news broadcasts, community hearings, and audio used as source material. The Audio reels titled "New Deal Films" correspond to a 16mm film, titled "Towards a Livable City" (Media ID 270.032 - Media ID: 270.0335) Descriptions are derived from the original cassette or container annotations and include title, date, the original format of audio, and the total running time (TRT).

Scope and Content

Scope and Content
